29 May 2012 18:02






No, I don't know it's name. I don't even know that the coin exists. All I know is that there is this cube, and it's an infohazard. The report doesn't say what it does, and I don't think about it too much because infohazards are nasty. For all I know it creates a chicken every time someone thinks that it's a sphere.

To clarify: SCP-1663 is the cube; the coin doesn't have a designation, because nobody knows that the coin exists.

Also, infohazards that are activated only by their SCP designation stretch my suspension of disbelief somewhat. The designation is not something inherited in the object, it's just a word we use to refer to it. Imagine some poor researcher thinking  and then his heads explodes because 2041 happened to be an infohazard. Most of our existing infohazards wouldn't work if you only know their number: 096 needs you to see his face, 964 can only change what it is, not what other people call it, and 1055 only reacts to fear.

(The fact that your fear 1055 once you know how it works is an example of a non-anomalous memetic effect, by the way. If you are unfamiliar with the concepts of death, pain and danger, then you wouldn't fear him and trigger his growth. But I digress.)

In the case of 1663 it's ambiguous whether knowing the sequence  triggers the effect, but if SCP-1663 is designation of the cube and the cube only, then keeping the coin in the cube should be reasonably safe either way.





